<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Use Shade Cloth Clips</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Hoop systems:</strong> clean attachment along the frame.</li>
    <li><strong>Permanent setups:</strong> consistent positioning.</li>
    <li><strong>Even coverage:</strong> reduces sagging.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Clips are best when you want a stable, repeatable structure.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Use Bungee Cords</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Windy areas:</strong> absorbs movement.</li>
    <li><strong>Temporary setups:</strong> quick install and removal.</li>
    <li><strong>Irregular frames:</strong> easier to adapt.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Bungees work best when flexibility matters more than precision.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Combined Setup (What Actually Works Best)</h2>

  <p>
    Many gardeners get the best results by combining both:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>use clips to attach shade cloth at key points</li>
    <li>use bungee cords to maintain tension across the structure</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This approach keeps the cloth secure while allowing movement where needed.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Over-tightening with Bungees</h3>
  <p>
    Too much tension can stress the frame or tear the fabric.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Too Few Attachment Points</h3>
  <p>
    This leads to sagging and uneven shading.
  </p>

  <h3>Relying on Only One Method</h3>
  <p>
    Clips or bungees alone often leave gaps in performance.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into a Shade Setup</h2>

  <p>
    The attachment method affects how well your shade cloth performs overall. A secure, evenly tensioned setup provides more consistent shading and lasts longer through changing conditions.
  </p>

